            <p>For non-native speakers, particularly from English, Urdu, or Bengali backgrounds, the distinction between the soft <strong>Ha (<span lang="ar" dir="rtl">هـ</span>)</strong> and the deep, friction-based <strong>Haa (<span lang="ar" dir="rtl">ح</span>)</strong> is the most persistent hurdle.</p>
            <p>The former originates from the bottom of the throat (<em>Aqsa al-Halq</em>), similar to the 'h' in the English word "home." The latter requires precise constriction in the middle of the throat (<em>Wasat al-Halq</em>).</p>
            <p>Why is this critical? Consider the word <em>"Al-Hamd"</em> (All Praise). If pronounced with a soft 'Ha', the word loses its specific Quranic gravity and can inadvertently change the meaning. Excellence in Tajweed requires the development of <strong>Muscular Awareness</strong>—training the epiglottis to respond to airflow with calibrated friction. Live feedback from a certified tutor is the only reliable way to ensure your throat is vibrating at the correct frequency.</p>
          </section>

